    {
      "id": "95ba39cd18fbe61c25d50b77fa47c321331b9753",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 263,
        "name": "Henri Doreau",
        "email": "henri.doreau@cea.fr",
        "username": "hdoreau"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 13:20:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI gave it a try but I'm afraid I lack a full understanding of what's happening with test_154a. I guess it might take me a while to fix it.\n\nSince this is a blocker someone more knowledgeable about lustre internals might want to take the relay.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "cdd0926934473be7efebc9e0d15b54acfd2d0d7b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 13:55:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nLU-1777.\n\n echo \"rename .lustre to itself\"\n fid=$($LFS path2fid $MOUNT)\n mrename $MOUNT/.lustre $MOUNT/.lustre/fid/$fid/.lustre &&\n    error \"rename .lustre to itself should fail.\"\n\nThis is not specific to $MOUNT and can be reproduced with an arbitrary directory. The Linux VFS assumes that the dcache is a tree and there is probably nothing Lustre cand do to affect this.\n\nFor this patch to go forward, I think this rename must be removed from 154a.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "fe128deb1d5265a367a7a127d64401a854009dda",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 15:23:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.4/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/1f150744-b3f7-11e2-b8f6-52540035b04c).  Ran 16 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "c3f12466757fb430ce296ba74fc4fa04aa27e87d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 17:34:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nJohn,\ndoes is it possible to just explicitly deny renaming of the .lustre directory?\n\nI'm fine with that, or with just disabling this rename test for now.  Either way, it needs to be refreshed so that it can pass and we can include it in 2.4.0.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "00750c154bc5f78d2d4d8843b36e27f1e7054b65",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 17:43:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: No score\n\n> John, does is it possible to just explicitly deny renaming of the .lustre directory?\n\nYes. But that's not the issue.\n\nThe deadlock is very early in the sys_rename() path, before any lustre methods are called. If rename() is given two directories, it will check to see if the dentries are the same and if not it will lock d_inode->i_mutex on each dentry. OBF allows us to violate the assumption in linux that the mapping from dir-dentries to dir-inodes is 1-1. Niu and I both concluded that it cannot be fixed without a kernel patch.\n\nI will disable the test.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "e4b84e7269f8c56608da377a8265a22b876f4c1a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
